VWhat is Computer Security, and Why Should I Care? (Part 2)
p333
sg123
Vjhamrick
p334
sS'comments'
p335
Vhttp://jhamrick.mit.edu/2010/08/04/what-is-computer-security-and-why-should-i-care-part-2/#comments
p336
sg127
g327
sg128
(lp337
g1
(g2
g3
(dp338
g41
S'http://jhamrick.mit.edu/feed/'
p339
sg24
S'text/html'
p340
sg29
Nsg44
V<h2><span>Hacking Websites and Computers</span></h2>\u000a<p>This is the second post in a series of blog posts about computer security:</p>\u000a<ul>\u000a<li><a href="http://jhamrick.mit.edu/2010/07/07/what-is-computer-security-and-why-should-i-care-part-1/">Part 1 &#8211; Introduction</a></li>\u000a<li><a href="http://jhamrick.mit.edu/2010/08/04/what-is-computer-security-and-why-should-i-care-part-2/">Part 2 &#8211; Hacking Websites and Computers</a></li>\u000a<li>Part 3 &#8211; Man-in-the-Middle Attacks</li>\u000a<li>Part 4 &#8211; Router Hacking</li>\u000a<li>Part 5 &#8211; Internet and Wireless Connection Snooping</li>\u000a</ul>\u000a<p>Recall Ben and Louis from the introduction. Both of them have houses, both of which are potential points of attack for Eve. Hopefully, both of them lock their doors and windows, or Eve could walk right in.  Even if they do lock the entrances to their houses, Eve might be a skilled lockpicker. When people have valuable possessions that they need to protect, they will buy high-grade locks that are difficult to pick in order to keep intruders out. With the exception of locking mechanisms themselves, physical security is relatively easy to judge because you can see it. If you have thicker doors and windows, they are harder to break down. If you have security guards, it is harder to sneak in.</p>\u000a<p>Unfortunately, computer security isn&#8217;t so obvious. Attacks are done electronically instead of physically, and you can&#8217;t see electricity (and even if you could, the signals that a computer processes are so complex that you would not be able to interpret them).  It is therefore very easy, so to speak, to leave the &#8220;front door&#8221; of your computer wide open.</p>\u000a<p>One might argue that it&#8217;s not a big deal for the average user, because who&#8217;s going to target them?  They don&#8217;t have anything of value, right?  Wrong.  Most people store passwords and credit card numbers on their computers.  If it&#8217;s easy to break in, why not?  Credit card numbers are a criminal&#8217;s goldmine, and passwords lead to more credit card numbers.  The computer itself is of value; attackers can use it to propagate attacks/viruses to even more computers.</p>\u000a<p>Furthermore, whenever you browse websites such as Facebook, Amazon, or Bank of America, you make the assumption that such sites are safe &#8212; i.e., that no one is going to break into said website and steal your data. Websites are nothing more than more computers, so the same vulnerabilities that exist on your computer probably also exist on those websites.  While there aren&#8217;t really any good ways to guarantee that a given website is following good security practices, it is important to be cognizant of what practices they should be following, so if you discover that they aren&#8217;t, you know to to stop trusting that website.</p>\u000a<h3><span>Install Security Updates</span></h3>\u000a<p>Certain programs run on your computer and &#8220;listen&#8221; on things called &#8220;ports&#8221;.  Imagine a giant building with thousands of doors to the outside.  Most of them are closed and bolted shut, but a few of them have employees guarding them.  Some employees are more alert than others, and some are more gullible than others.  This building is like your computer, the ports are the doors, and the programs are the employees.  Just as it is possible trick an employee into letting a thief inside, it is possible to &#8220;trick&#8221; programs into giving an attacker access to your computer.</p>\u000a<p>If you were the owner of such a building, you would make sure to keep your employees up-to-date on the sorts of people that try to get into your building, and what sort of lines they might use to get themselves in the door.  Likewise, as the owner of your computer, you should always make sure you have the latest updates &#8212; even if it means you have to reboot your computer, you should install them as soon as you can.  Update managers generally have an option to automatically download and install such updates; you should always turn this option on.  (Shameless plug: Linux users can avoid the need to reboot after such security updates by installing <a href="http://www.ksplice.com/">Ksplice</a>!)</p>\u000a<h3><span>Use Common Sense</span></h3>\u000a<p>All of us who have used a computer have probably, at some point, somehow gotten a virus or spyware.  As much as we would like to curse the makers of such software, it is undeniable that the majority of such software on our computers is <em>our fault</em>.  That&#8217;s right &#8212; nearly every piece of malicious software on your computer is there because at some point, you installed a sketchy program or opened an executable attachment in your email.  There are some viruses which propagate due to security holes (see the previous section), but for the most part, they spread because of human error.</p>\u000a<p>So, what do you do?  Your first line of defense is common sense.  What program are you installing?  Is it something written by an unreputable party?  Does it lack a user base?  It the program to be used for dubious purposes?  If the answer to any of these questions is yes, then the chances of the program being malicious is much higher than normal.  Do <em>not</em> install it unless you can verify that it is harmless.  If you are dealing with an email attachment, look at the email.  Is it from a stranger?  If it&#8217;s from someone you know, is it out-of-the-ordinary?  Is it an executable?  Again, if the answer to any of these questions is yes, do <em>not</em> open the attachment.</p>\u000a<p>Of course, none of us are perfect.  Occasionally, we make mistakes.  So, it is always a good idea to have a form of backup protection: anti-virus and anti-spyware programs should catch whatever you miss.  However, they are not perfect either, and don&#8217;t instantaneously have the most recent updates about which viruses are out there.  It is up to you to use common sense to throw out the majority of unscrupulous software that is presented to you.</p>\u000a<h3><span>Protect Your Data</span></h3>\u000a<p>Ben Bitdiddle keeps a note tacked to the corkboard next to his front door which has the location of and combination to his safe.  He also hangs his keys there.  If Eve were to break into Ben&#8217;s house, she wouldn&#8217;t have any trouble at all taking the money, because she would have instant access to where the data is kept and how to access it.  You might say that Ben is pretty stupid for leaving such sensitive information in such an obvious place, and you&#8217;d be right.</p>\u000a<p>Likewise, it is a bad idea to leave a list of passwords lying around.  Many people keep a digital list on their desktop, or write the passwords down and tape them nearby.  Any attacker who gets access to such computers would then have instant access to those accounts, and probably also instant access to your credit card numbers, social security numbers, phone numbers, etc.  &#8220;Ok,&#8221; you say. &#8220;I&#8217;ll hide them somewhere!&#8221;  This is also not a good idea.  Hiding sensitive information, also known as &#8220;security through obscurity&#8221;, is not real security.  If and when an attacker finds the hidden data, they will still have access to all of your personal information.  Security through obscurity can add an extra hurdle, but it is <em>never</em> sufficient to fully protect you.  Such protection only comes through encryption.</p>\u000a<p>Encryption is a way of coding data such that no one can read it unless they have the means to decrypt it (which generally entails having the correct password or key).  Any code counts as encryption, even pig latin &#8212; but you wouldn&#8217;t want to use pig latin to protect your data.  These days, sophisticated algorithms exist that are practically uncrackable (not entirely, but very difficult and time-consuming to do).</p>\u000a<p>You should use a plugin for your browser, such as LastPass or RoboForm, that will automatically generate unique passwords for every single site you visit, and encrypt them locally.  You can then sync the encrypted passwords between all of your computers, so you always have access to your websites.  All you need to remember is a single master password.  This adds a great deal of security because:</p>\u000a<ul>\u000a<li> You have a different password for every single site.  If somebody finds your password to one site, it doesn&#8217;t tell them anything about your other passwords.</li>\u000a<li> All of your passwords (except the master) are encrypted locally before being sent to the server, so even if somebody breaks into the server, they will be unable to view your passwords.</li>\u000a</ul>\u000a<p>But remember &#8212; <em>never, ever give your master password out or write it down</em>.  The only place it should exist is in your head.</p>\u000a<h3><span>What to Take Away</span></h3>\u000a<p>In general, the most important rule of thumb for computer security is to use common sense, as we have seen in this post, and as we will see in the next few posts as well.  A few good guidelines to follow are:</p>\u000a<ul>\u000a<li>Do use common sense.</li>\u000a<li>Do take security updates as soon as possible.</li>\u000a<li>Don&#8217;t install sketchy programs.</li>\u000a<li>Don&#8217;t open sketchy attachments, especially from unknown sources.</li>\u000a<li>Don&#8217;t store all your passwords (and other sensitive information) in a plaintext file.</li>\u000a<li>Do encrypt your passwords and other sensitive information.</li>\u000a<li>Don&#8217;t use the same password for every service.</li>\u000a</ul>\u000a<p>Next time, I&#8217;ll be discussing man-in-the-middle-attacks.  Stay tuned!</p>
