S'text/html'
p454
sg29
Nsg44
V<h2><span>Introduction</span></h2>\u000a<p>This is the first post in a series of blog posts about computer security:</p>\u000a<ul>\u000a<li><a href="http://jhamrick.mit.edu/2010/07/07/what-is-computer-security-and-why-should-i-care-part-1/">Part 1 &#8211; Introduction</a></li>\u000a<li><a href="http://jhamrick.mit.edu/2010/08/04/what-is-computer-security-and-why-should-i-care-part-2/">Part 2 &#8211; Hacking Websites and Computers</a></li>\u000a<li>Part 3 &#8211; Man-in-the-Middle Attacks</li>\u000a<li>Part 4 &#8211; Router Hacking</li>\u000a<li>Part 5 &#8211; Internet and Wireless Connection Snooping</li>\u000a</ul>\u000a<p>With computers and technology taking up such a large portion of our everyday lives, you would expect security to be rock-solid, or at least nearly so. Unfortunately, you would be mistaken. <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/06/business/06road.html?src=busln">Credit card fraud</a> is all too easy for even a novice, <a href="http://www.us-cert.gov/cas/tips/ST04-014.html">phishing</a> scams trick people into revealing passwords, credit card numbers, or worse, and <a href="http://mobile.darkreading.com/9287/show/70bccd37f24ee7581a6be43ea0c72e54/">fake accounts</a> lead people to trust non-existent or even stolen identities. Those examples only just scratch the surface. If you want to be safe on the internet and on your computer, you need to be savvy about it. Knowledge is power, and with knowledge, you can protect yourself.</p>\u000a<p>Let&#8217;s begin with an analogy. Our main actor, Louis Reasoner, has asked his cousin, Ben Bitdiddle, to send him $1000 in cash through the postal service (Ben owes Louis some money he lent him to buy a new computer). Well, sending cash through the mail isn&#8217;t very smart, but we&#8217;ll ignore that for a moment. So, there are five phases of the money&#8217;s journey:</p>\u000a<ol>\u000a<li>At Ben&#8217;s house</li>\u000a<li>In transit, from Ben&#8217;s house to the post office</li>\u000a<li>At the post office</li>\u000a<li>In transit, from the post office to Louis&#8217; house</li>\u000a<li>At Louis&#8217; house</li>\u000a</ol>\u000a<p>Unfortunately for Louis, his ex-girlfriend, Eve S. Dropper, has heard about the exchange and has decided that she wants the money (for various vengeful reasons, she believes that Louis owes it to her). Eve makes up her mind to somehow steal the money from Louis. How can she do it? Well, she has five opportunities, corresponding to the five stages above:</p>\u000a<ol>\u000a<li>She could break into Ben&#8217;s house and steal the money before he sends it</li>\u000a<li>She could waylay the postman and steal it from him, or she could pretend to be the postman</li>\u000a<li>She could break into the post office and steal it</li>\u000a<li>Same as #2 (except in transit to Louis&#8217; house)</li>\u000a<li>Same as #1 (except at Louis&#8217; house)</li>\u000a</ol>\u000a<p>Malicious hackers know of similar attacks in the realm of computers. Instead of Louis&#8217; house, the route to the post office, the post office, the route to Ben&#8217;s house, and Ben&#8217;s house, the computer analog might consist of your computer, your wireless network, your wireless router, the internet, and a website. Just as one might intercept a letter in the mail, one can intercept the data you send on the internet:</p>\u000a<ol>\u000a<li>Someone could hack into the website and steal the data</li>\u000a<li>Someone could &#8220;reroute&#8221; your connection and pretend to be the website, or they could listen in on your connection to the website</li>\u000a<li>Someone could hack into your router and reconfigure it</li>\u000a<li>Someone could listen in on your wireless network and steal the data</li>\u000a<li>Someone could hack into your computer and steal the data</li>\u000a</ol>\u000a<p>The most common attacks that take place over the internet these days fall into the categories of 1 and 4, but you should be aware and protected against all of them. In the next few posts, we&#8217;ll see how these attacks work, and how you can defend yourself from them.</p>
p455
stRp456
asg135
I00
